<paragraph id="5323CF59AB05FF8DFF1DB7ADCF05FE1B" blockId="10.[151,1436,1953,2014]" lastBlockId="11.[151,1437,151,464]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="482" pageId="10" pageNumber="481">
TCEC made additional observations on the shelters of 
<taxonomicName id="949CB4DAAB05FF8CFC8CB7AECF8CF871" authorityName="Collins &amp; Larsen" authorityYear="1994" box="[774,974,1953,1978]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Abantis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="481" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bamptoni">
<emphasis id="61E8134BAB05FF8CFC8CB7AECF8CF871" box="[774,974,1953,1978]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="481">Abantis bamptoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on 
<taxonomicName id="949CB4DAAB05FF8CFC71B7ACC8FBF871" box="[1019,1209,1953,1978]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" genus="Uapaca" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="10" pageNumber="481" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kirkiana">
<emphasis id="61E8134BAB05FF8CFC71B7ACC8FBF871" box="[1019,1209,1953,1978]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="481">Uapaca kirkiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="949CB4DAAB05FF8CFB43B7AEC934F871" authorityName="" authorityYear="1820" box="[1225,1398,1953,1978]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="10" pageNumber="481" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Phyllanthaceae</taxonomicName>
) in Mutinondo Wilderness, Mpika, Zambia, in 
<date id="2722E999AB05FF8CFD03B7C9CF63F815" box="[649,801,1990,2014]" pageId="10" pageNumber="481" value="2014-01">January 2014</date>
(
<figureCitation id="CBA7D3DCAB05FF8CFCB8B7CACF99F815" box="[818,987,1989,2014]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 13" captionStart-1="FIGURE 14" captionStartId-0="11.[151,250,1636,1658]" captionStartId-1="12.[151,250,1062,1084]" captionTargetBox-0="[151,1436,519,1611]" captionTargetBox-1="[151,1436,555,1038]" captionTargetId-0="figure@11.[151,1436,519,1611]" captionTargetId-1="figure@12.[151,1436,555,1038]" captionTargetPageId-0="11" captionTargetPageId-1="12" captionText-0="FIGURE 13. Early leaf shelters of Abantis bamptoni on Uapaca kirkiana, Mutinondo Wilderness, Zambia, Jan 2014 [TCEC]. 1, view of whole leaf (about 25 cm long); 2, hatched ovum, with site of first shelter and instar 1 feeding; 3, shelter 2 freshly cut and turned over; 4, as  3, but one day later; 5, as  4, viewed from the side." captionText-1="FIGURE 14. Final leaf shelter of Abantis bamptoni on Uapaca kirkiana, Mutinondo Wilderness, Zambia, Jan 2014 [TCEC]. 1, shelter in situ; note the caterpillar head is just visible; 2, view of whole leaf (about 25 cm long)." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/855823/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/855825/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="481">Figures 13â€“14</figureCitation>
). Observations were made on the first two shelters of one individual (
<figureCitation id="CBA7D3DCAB04FF8DFE74B098CE32FF7B" box="[510,624,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1636,1658]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,519,1611]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,519,1611]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 13. Early leaf shelters of Abantis bamptoni on Uapaca kirkiana, Mutinondo Wilderness, Zambia, Jan 2014 [TCEC]. 1, view of whole leaf (about 25 cm long); 2, hatched ovum, with site of first shelter and instar 1 feeding; 3, shelter 2 freshly cut and turned over; 4, as  3, but one day later; 5, as  4, viewed from the side." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/855823/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="482">Figure 13</figureCitation>
). The whole leaf in situ in Figure 13.1 shows the site of the first leaf shelter, and the second leaf shelter. Figure 13.2 is an enlargement of the first shelter and surrounding area, with feeding damage mostly to the leaf surface areas, seldom perforating the leaf. The hatched ovum can be seen, adjacent to the hole where the shelter lid was cut out, and it appears that the shelter covered the small patch of surface feeding to the right of the cut portion, as there is evidence of silking over that area. Since the priority of the neonate caterpillar would be to make its leaf shelter, we suggest that the first feeding thereafter was on the floor of the shelter. The flap of the shelter is missing; this suggests the flap may have been detached by the caterpillar, since normally when a the first shelter is unoccupied due to the death of the caterpillar, the flap remains attached for a long time, and it can be quite hard to open it for examination.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="07E39FD1AB04FF8DFF1DB66BCFC9F97C" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/855823/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="482" targetBox="[151,1436,519,1611]" targetPageId="11">
<paragraph id="5323CF59AB04FF8DFF1DB66BCFC9F97C" blockId="11.[151,1437,1636,1719]" pageId="11" pageNumber="482">
<emphasis id="61E8134BAB04FF8DFF1DB66BCD5BF9B2" bold="true" box="[151,281,1636,1658]" pageId="11" pageNumber="482">FIGURE 13</emphasis>
. Early leaf shelters of 
<taxonomicName id="949CB4DAAB04FF8DFD8EB66BCEFAF9B1" authorityName="Collins &amp; Larsen" authorityYear="1994" box="[516,696,1636,1658]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Abantis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="482" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bamptoni">
<emphasis id="61E8134BAB04FF8DFD8EB66BCEFAF9B1" box="[516,696,1636,1658]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="482">Abantis bamptoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on 
<taxonomicName id="949CB4DAAB04FF8DFD57B66AC8C2F9B1" authority=", Mutinondo Wilderness" authorityName="Mutinondo Wilderness" box="[733,1152,1636,1658]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" genus="Uapaca" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="11" pageNumber="482" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kirkiana">
<emphasis id="61E8134BAB04FF8DFD57B66ACFCAF9B1" box="[733,904,1636,1658]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="482">Uapaca kirkiana</emphasis>
, Mutinondo Wilderness
</taxonomicName>
, Zambia, Jan 2014 [TCEC]. 
<emphasis id="61E8134BAB04FF8DFF1DB68CCCE6F953" bold="true" box="[151,164,1667,1688]" pageId="11" pageNumber="482">1</emphasis>
, view of whole leaf (about 25cm long); 
<emphasis id="61E8134BAB04FF8DFDB7B68CCE0BF953" bold="true" box="[573,585,1667,1688]" pageId="11" pageNumber="482">2</emphasis>
, hatched ovum, with site of first shelter and instar 1 feeding; 
<emphasis id="61E8134BAB04FF8DFB30B68CC885F953" bold="true" box="[1210,1223,1667,1688]" pageId="11" pageNumber="482">3</emphasis>
, shelter 2 freshly cut and turned over; 
<emphasis id="61E8134BAB04FF8DFEC9B6AECD12F97D" bold="true" box="[323,336,1697,1718]" pageId="11" pageNumber="482">4</emphasis>
, as #3, but one day later; 
<emphasis id="61E8134BAB04FF8DFDDEB6ADCE22F97C" bold="true" box="[596,608,1698,1719]" pageId="11" pageNumber="482">5</emphasis>
, as #4, viewed from the side.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="1B869CD2AB04FF8AFF4DB6EBC918FE3E" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="483" pageId="11" pageNumber="482" type="description">
<paragraph id="5323CF59AB04FF8AFF4DB6EBCE9DFED6" blockId="11.[151,1437,1764,2005]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1437,151,501]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="483" pageId="11" pageNumber="482">Figure 13.3 is an enlargement of the freshly cut second shelter, which contained a second instar caterpillar. The edges of the cut are still green, as is the chewed material round the edge of the cut. Note that the caterpillar did not eat the chewed material. During shelter construction, the caterpillar is exposed and vulnerable to predators and weather; hence speed of shelter construction is the priority, and eating and digesting the material cut to make the shelter would have delayed completion. At this stage the flap has not been secured to the leaf surface, but already a tuck can be seen near the top of the flap in the figure. To make this, the caterpillar eats from the leaf upper surface (of the flap within the shelter) to weaken the underside of the roof so that it is easy to pull together with silk. It does not actually cut through the flap. Figure 13.4 is of the same shelter a day later. The flap has been secured to the leaf surface, and the lid on each side of the notch pulled together with silk (Figure 13.5) to form the entrance, and making the underside of the lid concave to form the shelter. The surface of the cut and the chewed material are now dry and brown, as is the flap itself.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5323CF59AB03FF8AFF4DB128C918FE3E" blockId="12.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="12" pageNumber="483">
<materialsCitation id="E3F4C504AB03FF8AFF4DB128C918FE3E" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="1587262076" location="A" pageId="12" pageNumber="483" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="A">
The final shelter shown in situ in 
<figureCitation id="CBA7D3DCAB03FF8AFDB6B128CEEAFE8B" box="[572,680,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1062,1084]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,555,1038]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,555,1038]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 14. Final leaf shelter of Abantis bamptoni on Uapaca kirkiana, Mutinondo Wilderness, Zambia, Jan 2014 [TCEC]. 1, shelter in situ; note the caterpillar head is just visible; 2, view of whole leaf (about 25 cm long)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/855825/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="483">Figure 14</figureCitation>
was also documented on the same occasion. Figure 14.1 shows the shelter in details and Figure 14.2 shows the whole leaf. 
<collectingRegion id="915801BBAB03FF8AFCA7B143CF03FEAF" box="[813,833,332,356]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="12" pageNumber="483">A</collectingRegion>
more or less bell shaped flap was cut from the leaf margin, across one major vein and hinged on a second main vein. The bell-shaped flap was then swivelled underneath the distal part of the leaf held with silk. Silk threads seem to have been used to make both surfaces arched, creating a pocket between them. There is a deep notch in the flap cut across the base of cut main vein, and at the internal end of this, silk has been used to pull the sides together, contributing to the arching of the flap.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
